Recommendations for Learning

Proceed step-by-step.

  • Each concept builds on previous concepts.
  • Doing the reading when instructed by async.
    • We have interwoven reading and video to help you master each concept before moving on.
  • If things become unclear, go back and rewatch / reread. (This is normal!)
  • Step-by-step is so important. Learning math is tough and you wont understand the direction of the argument at first. But you have to put in the hours and trust that there is a progression! you focus on one piece until you learn it, then move on to the next piece.
  • By integrating reading and video, we can integrate explain, and set the location of what youre going to read of have just read.
  • We know that this is probably different from any class youve taken before; but, thats because in an online format like this were not bound by the same constraints as when we have to be in person.
  • In this format were optimizing for maximum learning, not ease of scheduling.

Build a schedule for your studying.

  • Find time when you feel calm and can focus on the material.
  • If possible, we recommend splitting your study time over multiple days.
    • We have divided most units into parts for this purpose.

We think that youll be able to learn as much as possible by spreading your learning across a few days. - We also know that this kind of very active learning is tiring; after about 1.5 or 2 hours youre likely to be tired. - Stop for the evening, and let that learning integrate and come back to the next section the following day.

Study together.

  • Schedule study sections
  • Schedule peer discussion sections
  • Schedule Q&A times about homework with your peers.

You all the community of students are the best resource in the program.

Attend Office Hours.

  • You can attend the office hours of any instructor.
  • You can attend as many office hours each week as you want.
  • Bring your homework problems, or more general questions, or show up just to chat.

Maximize learning, not points.

  • Theres no reason to score points on assignments or tests if you havent learned the concept.
  • The fundamentals will be important throughout MIDS and beyond.
  • The process of moving from real-world problem setup into the constrained math objects and back is a huge part of what creates value as a data scientist.
  • Interviews focus on this because data scientists work focuses on this. We dont ask plug-and-chug problems in this class. 99% of your time will be spent connecting words in English to mathematical objects. Its normal not to know what formula to apply - once you do, youre almost done. If you feel lost, try drawing a picture, start by defining variables, and try to express the concept you want to find in terms of those variables.

Probability Theory

Probability

  • Probability is a system of reasoning that we use to model the world under incomplete information
  • This model underlies virtually every other model youll ever use

Defining a Sample Space

  • For each of the following experiments, how would you define the sample space, \(\Omega\)?
    • Rolling a six sided die
    • Drawing a five-card poker hand
    • Choosing 1,000 Berkeley students for a survey about on-campus student health and well-being

Working with a Sample Space, Part I

  1. For one roll of a six-sided die:
    1. What is the sample space, \(\Omega\)?
    2. How many elements exist in \(\Omega\)?
    3. What is an example of an event, \(\omega\) that could occur?

Working with a Sample Space, Part II

  1. For one roll of TWO six-sided die:
    1. What is the sample space, \(\Omega\)?
    2. How many elements exist in \(\Omega\)?
    3. Starting from two dice with six faces which would cause \(\Omega\) increase faster: Adding a new die, or adding a new face to existing die?

Working with a Sample Space, Part III

  1. For a 52-card poker deck (i.e.a deck that contains 13 ranks grouped by four suits):
    1. What is the sample space \(\Omega\)?
    2. How many elements exist in \(\Omega\)?
    3. What is an example of an event that has five cards in it?
    4. How many ways can you produce an arbitrary five-card event?
    5. What is the probability of getting one particular event?
    6. Bonus: What elements are in the four-card event that is the worst hand you could have?

Working with a Sample Space, Part IV

  1. For a random sample of 1,000 Berkeley students:
    1. What is the sample space, \(\Omega\)?
    2. How big is \(\Omega\)? How many elements does it contain?
    3. What is an example of an event that could occur within the sample space?
    4. Can a single person be in the space twice? Why or why not?

Working with a Sample Sapce, Part V

  1. Suppose that youre sitting in a surf lineup, and you have to pick a wave that is the right height. Too small, and you wont get anywhere, too large and youll get crushed.
    1. What is the sample space for wave height, \(\Omega\)?
    2. How big is \(\Omega\)? How many elements does it contain?
    3. What is an example of an event that could occur within the sample space?
    4. If you paddle at 10 waves, how large is the sample space?

Total Probability

Total Probability, Part I

  • Below is written the law of total probability.
  • Read the math aloud, and explain what it means.

\[ P(B) = \sum_{i=1}^{N} P(A_{i} \cap B) = \sum_{i=1}^{N}P(B|A_{i})P(A_{i}) \]

Playing Catchup

Suppose youre taking a statistics class and that in each week you are either caught up or behind on the readings.

  • It is difficult to incorporate a new class in to your schedule so the probability that you will be caught up in Week 1, having viewed all async and completed the pre class exercises before the live session, is 0.7.
  • From then on, if you are caught up in a given week, the probability that you will be caught up in the next week is 0.7.
  • If you are behind in a given week, the probability that you will be caught up in the next week is 0.4.
  • What is the probability that you are caught up in week 3?

Fatal Office Involved Shootings

  • Johnson et al.model purports to estimate the effect of officer race in officer involved shootings.

Claim: White officers are not more likely to shoot minority civilians than non-White [sic] officers.

Data: Among those people who were shot, what proportion are minority civilians?

  • What is the difference between these two statements?
  • If the claim were to be true, what policy action would you take?
  • Because we cant evaluate whether the claim is true, what would happen if you took the recommended policy action?
  • One way to more clearly illustrate the impossibility of this data to adjudicate this claim is to move it to its primal events and then cast it into words that might be more familiar.
  • Claim: Kids are more likely to eat brussels sprouts than adults
  • Data: Among people who eat, what proportion are kids?
  • Clearly, the data produced has no bearing on the question at hand

Apply Bayes Theorem

(Optional) Coronavirus Testing

Coronavirus Testing, Part I

  • Many forms of coronavirus testing works in the following way:
    • A test measures the levels of a particular immunoglobulin, if these levels are higher/lower than some threshold the test declares a qualitative assessment: positive/negative.
    • By raising the threshold that the immunoglobulin need to cross, the test will have fewer false-positive results; by lowering the threshold that the immunoglobulin need to cross the test will have fewer false-negative results.

Coronavirus Testing, Part II

  • Let \(T\) be the event that a test comes up positive.

  • Let \(C\) be the event that an individual has coronavirus.

  • Let \(R\) be the population disease rate.

  • Suppose that you set the threshold on the test such that \(P(T|C) = 0.94\) and \(P(T^C|C^C) = 0.96\).

  • Suppose that you believe the population prevelance of Coronavirus to be 10% of the population.

Coronavirus Testing, Part III

  1. What is the probability that a person has coronavirus, given they present a positive result?
  2. What is the probability that a person does not have coronavirus, given they present a positive result?
  3. What is the probability that a person has coronavirus, given than they present two positive results?
  4. What is the probability that a person has coronavirus, given that they present one positive and one negative result?

Coronavirus Testing, Part IV

  • What if instead there was a lot of undetected coronavirus in the population? Rather than 10% of the population being affected, 30% of the population has the disease.
  1. What is the probability that a person has coronavirus, given they present a positive result?
  2. What is the probablity that a person does not have coronavirus, given they present a positive result?
  3. Are you surprised by how much these values change?
